 concepts of the "normal" were defined. One of the few histories to take into consideration homosexuality in both women and men, Terry's work also stands out in its refusal to erase the agency of people classified as abnormal. She documents the myriad ways that gays, lesbians, and other sexual minorities have coauthored, resisted, and transformed the most powerful and authoritative modern truths about sex. Proposing this history as a "useable past," An American Obsession is an indispensable contribution to the study of American cultural history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  ahomosexuality, sexuality, normative, medicine, psychology, psychiatry, order, social norms, abnormal, other, gay, lesbian, nonfiction, history, sociology, queer, lgbtq, lgbt, lgbtqia, perversion, medicalization, pathologization, fluidity, criminalization, difference, science, sexology, danger, sin, gender, pleasure, fear, kinsey, religion, pulp fiction, journalism, committee for the study of sex variants, transgression, havelock ellis, krafft-ebing, magnus hirschfeld, race, class.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package Archive 1990-1999z978311066785140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226793689423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226793689/original  a978-3-11-066785-1  University of Chicago Press eBook Package Archive 1990-1999c1990d1999  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles